 Qualifications 
 Strong background in coaching, and/or leadership; intervention experience a plus 
 Previous experience planning, developing, and facilitating professional development
 Ability to track and analyze quantitative and qualitative data to discover trends and act strategically and effectively to improve instructional quality and academic achievement 
 Strong communications skills with the ability to influence people; Transparent communicator who delivers feedback in a direct and compelling way that inspires immediate improvement 
 Strong organization and time management skills 
 An unrelenting commitment to constant learning and improvement, in both your own work and the work of others 
 Willingness to work non-standard hours 
 
 Experience 
 Have at least six months training experience (preferably in a BPO/Call center environment) with a proven track record of raising student achievement 
 Have at least six months instructional coaching or leadership experience (or similar) with a proven track record of improving learning and development quality 
 Know strong instructional practices when you see them. Whether you are watching an instructor deliver a lesson or looking at student performance data, you can identify areas where practice is effective and suggest ideas to improve immediately and in the long-term 
 Familiarity and/or experience with leadership observation and feedback processes 
 Familiarity and/or experience with data-driven decision making in a classroom setting environment 
 Ability to facilitate professional development for instructors, leaders, and other stakeholders both in-person and virtually 
 
 Specific responsibilities include: 
 
 Observations/Data Gathering 
 Conduct classroom observations and/or coaching sessions with program supervisors to measure and ensure the instructional health of our programs 
 Regularly co-plan and engage in post-observation feedback sessions with supervisors and instructors
 Collect and analyze multiple forms of data to determine specific program, supervisor, and instructor needs; build supervisor capacity on how to do this process. 
